        <body>
            <div type="edition" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="grc">
                <ab>
                  <lb n="1"/><w lemma="φῶς"><expan><abbr>Φ</abbr><ex>ῶς</ex></expan><am>&#x00A0;῀&#x00A0;</am></w> <milestone unit="column"/> Χ
                  <lb n="2"/>Φ <milestone unit="column"/> Ι
                </ab> 
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
               <listApp>
                   <app loc="2"><rdg source="#Sacopoulo1966">Φ | (Π)</rdg></app>
               </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p>Unknown</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
             <p>The naos and narthex of Asinou contain numerous cryptograms that have been previously discussed in literature (<bibl><ptr target="#Rhoby2009"/>,<citedRange> 344-5</citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><ptr target="#Ševčenko2012"/>,<citedRange> 84-5</citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><ptr target="#Kalopissi-Verti2012"/>,<citedRange> 190-2</citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><ptr target="#MoutafovRhoby2012"/>,<citedRange> 181-7</citedRange></bibl>). This particular cryptic inscription has not yet been deciphered. The three opening letters resemble the common formula ΦΧΦΠ, which is often connected with the cross. The final letter/abbreviation could be interpreted as ἱκέταις. The  ΦΠ combination, which appears on the east jamb of the north entrance to the naos, may also be related to the same tetragram (ΦΧΦΠ) (<bibl><ptr target="#Ševčenko2012"/>,<citedRange> 85</citedRange></bibl>)</p></div>
